[[Image:memorial-keystone-1.jpg|thumb|right|Example of keystone at the Hurricane Monument.]] [[Image:memorial-keystone-2.jpg|thumb|right|Example of keystone at the Hurricane Monument.]] [[File:The Florida Keys Memorial, view of monument 4856.jpg|thumb|right|The monument itself]] '''Keystone''' is a type of [[limestone]], or [[coral rag]], quarried in the [[Florida Keys]], in particular from [[Windley Key]] [[fossil]] quarry, which is now a [[Windley Key Fossil Reef Geological State Park|State Park]] of [[Florida]]. The limestone is [[Pleistocene]] in age, and the rock primarily consists of [[Scleractinia|scleractinian]] coral, such as [[Elkhorn coral]] and [[Brain coral]]. [[Image:Fossil_Reef_Windley_Key_1.jpg|thumb|left|Example of fossil [[Brain coral]] (''Diploria'') at the [[Windley Key Fossil Reef Geological State Park|quarry]]. US Quarter near top for scale.]] The Hurricane Monument, commemorating victims of the [[Labor Day Hurricane of 1935]], and located at mile marker 82 on [[U.S. Route 1 in Florida|U.S. Route 1]] near [[Islamorada, Florida|Islamorada]], is constructed of keystone, as is the [[David W. Dyer Federal Building and United States Courthouse]].
